Chapter 1–3: High-Value Notes (what to actually remember)
🚀 1. Memory hierarchy dominates performance

Where your data lives matters more than your algorithm (after a point)

Latency ladder (rough intuition):

L1 → ~1–4 cycles
L2 → ~10 cycles
L3 → ~30–50 cycles
RAM → ~100–300+ cycles

👉 One cache miss can destroy performance

🔥 2. Cache lines (NOT individual variables)

CPU moves data in cache lines (usually 64 bytes)

Implications:

touching 1 byte → loads 64 bytes
good if you use neighbors (spatial locality)
bad if you don’t (waste bandwidth)
🧠 3. Locality is EVERYTHING
Spatial locality
access nearby memory → fast
Temporal locality
reuse same data → stays in cache

👉 This is why:

arrays > linked lists
vectors > pointer chasing
🔥 4. Sequential access = best case

Hardware prefetchers + burst DRAM love predictable patterns

sequential → near peak bandwidth
random → destroys performance

👉 This is one of the biggest real-world optimizations

💥 5. Pointer chasing is terrible

Linked lists, trees, graphs:

no spatial locality
no prefetching
constant cache misses

👉 Each step can cost ~100+ cycles

⚠️ 6. Working set size matters

If your working set fits in cache → fast
If not → performance collapses

Important thresholds:

fits in L1 → 🔥
fits in L2/L3 → 😐
spills to RAM → 🐢
🚀 7. Bandwidth becomes the bottleneck

When working set is large:

You are limited by memory bandwidth, not CPU

adding threads ≠ linear speedup
memory becomes the choke point
💥 8. Writes are MUCH more expensive than reads

Because of:

MESI (ownership / invalidation)
writebacks
RFO (Read For Ownership)

👉 Key idea:

Writes can be 10–20× slower than reads in worst cases

🔥 9. False sharing (VERY IMPORTANT)

Two threads writing different variables on the same cache line

Result:

cache line bounces between cores
MESI invalidations
massive slowdown

👉 This is one of the most important real-world bugs

🧠 10. Multithreading ≠ free speed

Limits:

shared memory bandwidth
cache coherence traffic
shared caches

👉 Often:

2 threads scale okay
4+ threads → diminishing returns
⚠️ 11. Instruction cache matters too
code has strong locality (loops)
L1i keeps execution fast
self-modifying code breaks assumptions → bad
🔧 12. TLB (address translation) matters

Virtual → physical translation is cached

large working sets → TLB misses
adds extra latency

👉 Hidden performance cliff

⚡ 13. Critical word & early restart
CPU only needs part of cache line to continue
tries to fetch that first

👉 small optimization, but real

🧠 14. Hardware prefetching
CPU predicts future accesses
works well for sequential patterns
fails for random access
🔥 15. DRAM prefers sequential access
burst mode → fast
random access → slow

👉 aligns with “sequential is king”

🧠 The META insight (most important)

If you remember ONE thing:

Performance = data layout + access pattern, not just algorithms

🚀 Practical rules (what you should actually do in C++)

These are gold for interviews + real systems:

Use contiguous memory (arrays, vectors)
Avoid pointer chasing
Batch work to fit in cache
Minimize writes, especially shared writes
Avoid false sharing (pad data if needed)
Prefer sequential access patterns
Be careful with multithreading on memory-heavy tasks
